Text: with India accounting for the highest number of deaths from this disease, most diagnoses still take place when it is too late for recovery to take place. most diagnosis still rely on an age old Jones Criteria which when revised, took no account of specific developing country need
Name: dreamingofchocolatetart

Text: one of the many illnesses which suffer from this apathy is rheumatic fever - recognised as an illness of the poor, developing world, an illness capable of causing death AND causing active deaths today, for which international funding has been poor and absent
Name: dreamingofchocolatetart

Text: the same criteria is taught in medical schools, is learnt by developing country doctors who will possibly encounter these illnesses. however the lack of context in these criteria make diagnosis tough and rare
Name: dreamingofchocolatetart

Text: diagnostic criteria remain age old, while testing improves, creating all the more confusion. doctors miss country specific region specific symptoms of illnesses - while the international community hails the presence of a 30 year old diagnostic criteria
Name: dreamingofchocolatetart

Text: the result: poor marginalised segments in developing countries with zero ability to amass and put policy pressure on governments suffer as they are diagnosed based on age old criteria based on guess what - based on how illnesses present themselves in white males
Name: dreamingofchocolatetart

Text: as a result, diagnostic criteria get rarely reviewed. developing countries themselves with limited resources do not fund better diagnostic criteria for these illnesses. while the international community seem apathetic to illnesses which aren't right in front of them
Name: dreamingofchocolatetart

Text: lets talk about the developing-developed country dichotomy in medical research, and more specifically at the WHO. There is little to no effort in modifying international guidelines for the diagnosis of illnesses which are recognised as 'developing country illnesses'
Name: dreamingofchocolatetart

Text: this should be an opportunity to have responsible discourse around mental illness, and how it can affect anyone. an opportunity to educate, not to reinforce notions of mental illness that are archaic by themselves.

Text: @hmlakdawala 12. Not just for me, but for many victims, whose hearts broke while making what you call this 'conscious choice'
Name: dreamingofchocolatetart

Text: @hmlakdawala 11. While these may not be 'real problems' as you define them, honestly, I did not need the wave of self-blame that followed reading a tweet of this kind.
Name: dreamingofchocolatetart

Text: @hmlakdawala 10. It is a systematic failure when I was required to fly into another city to submit my complaint. And when I lacked the support of my professors, as well as my parents.
Name: dreamingofchocolatetart

Text: @hmlakdawala 9. I was not a perfect victim in my assault. And I had seen the way imperfect victims were treated in ICC proceedings. It is a systematic failure when my attempts to approach ICC representatives were met with insensitivity.
Name: dreamingofchocolatetart

Text: @hmlakdawala 8. I do not know why you believe you have a right to discuss such an issue, which has ruined the lives of many, in such a callous way. But equally, I believed that I had a right to respond as well.
Name: dreamingofchocolatetart

Text: @hmlakdawala 7. There are no real, and not real reasons for choosing to not report. It is a lot more complicated than that. The ICC system is broken, in that it does not adequately provide for measures to address cross-university assaults, its implementation is very questionable
Name: dreamingofchocolatetart

Text: @hmlakdawala Also, in the comments you say, 'Victimhood ends when a conscious choice is made to not report'. I would say, victimhood doesn't exist for you to determine. Sexual assault haunts the survivors for ages, and not reporting is only a part of the self blame that follows it.
Name: dreamingofchocolatetart

Text: @hmlakdawala 5. Further, I do not really think that anyone has any right to call anyone a 'real victim' or not. That phrasing itself is problematic. Months after my assault, I doubted whether I was what you call a real victim. And this only led to me feeling like absolute crap about myself.
Name: dreamingofchocolatetart

Text: @hmlakdawala 4. These are personal experiences, and you could argue that these are not systematic failures, but a lack of trust in the system is not something I consciously chose. It's something I saw all around me. And if that isn't a systematic failure, I do not know what is.
Name: dreamingofchocolatetart

Text: @hmlakdawala 3. Never once have I seen an ICC proceeding which was carried on with the respect and sensitivity that the matters it deals with deserve. Never have I also seen an ICC proceeding resulting in anything except slut shaming for the victim.
Name: dreamingofchocolatetart

Text: @hmlakdawala 2. I am myself who you would call a 'victim educated about the law'. And when you refer to a presumption that reporting will not amount to much, the reason for this presumption is the very way women see this system work around them.
Name: dreamingofchocolatetart
